    <p><em>Area Between Curves</em></p>

    <p>Our study of area in the context of rectangular functions led naturally to finding area bounded between curves. We consider the same in the context of polar functions. <index><main>polar</main><sub>functions!area between curves</sub></index></p>

    <p>Consider the shaded region shown in <xref ref="fig_polarea3">Figure</xref>. We can find the area of this region by computing the area bounded by <m>r_2=f_2(\theta)</m> and subtracting the area bounded by <m>r_1=f_1(\theta)</m> on <m>[\alpha,\beta]</m>. Thus
      <me>
        \text{ Area } \ = \ \frac12\int_\alpha^\beta r_2^{\,2}\ d\theta - \frac12\int_\alpha^\beta r_1^{\,2}\ d\theta = \frac12\int_\alpha^\beta \big(r_2^{\,2}-r_1^{\,2}\big)\ d\theta.
      </me>
    </p>

