      <solution>
        <p>We need to find the points of intersection between these two functions. Setting them equal to each other, we find:
          <md>
            <mrow>1+\cos(\theta) \amp = 3\cos(\theta) </mrow>
            <mrow>\cos(\theta) \amp =1/2</mrow>
            <mrow>\theta \amp = \pm \pi/3</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>Thus we integrate <m>\frac12\big((3\cos(\theta) )^2-(1+\cos(\theta) )^2\big)</m> on <m>[-\pi/3,\pi/3]</m>.
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{ Area }  \amp = \frac12\int_{-\pi/3}^{\pi/3} \big((3\cos(\theta) )^2-(1+\cos(\theta) )^2\big)\ d\theta</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac12\int_{-\pi/3}^{\pi/3} \big( 8\cos^2(\theta) -2\cos(\theta) -1\big)\ d\theta</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \big(2\sin(2\theta) - 2\sin(\theta) +3\theta\big)\Bigg|_{-\pi/3}^{\pi/3}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = 2\pi.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>Amazingly enough, the area between these curves has a <q>nice</q> value.</p>
      </solution>
